Obviously , to perform optimally , an office should provide a quiet and calm workspace , so that the employees can focus on their jobs and they wo not be distracted during work time . Therefore , closed workstations or cubicles seem like the perfect solution to optimise the employees ' performances . On the other hand , how long can you really stay focused on your own in a boring room ? Employees in enclosed workstations often catch themselves staring at a blank wall , while people in open floor plan designed offices are more motivated to work . The reason for this is that seeing other people work is very motivating and increases your own productivity . Despite the fact that there is more noise and employees can easily get distracted because of small talk and chats with co -workers , they will probably work harder than they would in an enclosed workspace . In addition to this , it is easier for the boss or manager to check in on his employees in an open office , since he can just walk through the workspace . The employees will feel more pressure to continue to work when they know they are being watched , whereas the temptation to play a game on your computer in the enclosed workspace , since no one notices anyway , much bigger . To summarize , an enclosed workspace might seem to improve the employees ' productivity at first sight , but in my opinion , an open office is more effective . A little chat once in a while is not that bad , as long as employees are inspired and motivated most of the time . 
