In the contemporary society , medical doctors have a tendency to work in urban areas , in lieu of rural areas , which leads to many problems . In this essay , the main contributors to this trend , in conjunction with some proposed solutions to tackle this issue , will be discussed . Most medical doctors choose to develop their career in cities because they believe that it will provide them with a variety of opportunities to be more successful and earn more money for life . In rural areas , local hospitals do not have enough medical equipment , good facilities , . . . to help doctors improve their professional skills . The opposite is true for urban areas , doctors can not only get access to modern medical technology but also have a special training , even studying abroad to broaden their horizons and have professional qualifications . Moreover , it is undeniable that the salary and rewards paid to medical doctors in cities are usually higher than those in the countryside . Therefore , their standard of living , as well as education , entertainment for their children , families are much better when compared with living in rural areas . However , the rise of this issue has caused some serious drawbacks that both local authorities and the government should not ignore and co -operate together to address them . Most medical doctors leave for the cities because of the chances and money , so local authorities and the government should impose policies to raise salaries and have more professional training for alluring highly qualified doctors . By upgrading facilities , local authorities and the government can help doctors be more confident to treat victims and still work in rural areas . Furthermore , the government should have a positive effect on the doctors ' minds , which helps them realize that their mission is to rescue patients and heal their pains , irrespective of where they live . In conclusion , because of the salary and opportunities to develop , medical doctors decide to work in urban areas . The aforementioned reasons lay an adequate foundation for more policies , more encouragement to be introduced by authorities and the government to interest qualified doctors in working in rural areas . 
