Some employers think that working in separated and specified spaces is better than in open offices . In my opinion , it depends on the type of work and job that the company is doing . If the work done by employees demands deep focus , a shared office is not a good idea . The distraction caused by others will drain the employees ' concentration and the quality of work will be low . For example , in a programming office , the workers need a silent environment so they can focus on their codes , and a noisy place or a place full of movement will not let them centralize on their work . On the other hand , some type of work need a shared office since contacting with other colleagues during work time will generate more ideas and can bring creativity among co -workers . Furthermore , some projects are defined to be done in a team and open design offices can make the results more effective as the team members are constantly in touch with each other and all the team knows the progress of the project and what will be the next step . 
