Whether some students decide to leave and live by themselves or stay at their parents ' house , both choices have positive and negative aspects . For example , students who move out can face difficulties such as working and paying the rent while still attending courses and prepare for exams . This type of life can surely make them grow and be more responsible , but it can also overstress and put too much on their shoulders , which a 20 -year -old person may not be ready to manage in a balanced way . Otherwise , staying at your parents ' house could result easy in terms of organisation or money management . But even in this case , there could be some problems , such as the stress generated by college life and having to deal with your parents every day . The most important thing is that young students takes responsibility for their actions and choose wisely whatever the road they decide to follow . 
This last year showed everyone how crucial being active is . Studies show that a majority of people gained weight during the pandemic and , what is more , their condition also decreased . Some sport was difficult before the pandemic , therefore , is it necessary to force everyone to do sport 3 times per week ? What if schools came up with the solution which would suit everyone 's abilities ? In my opinion , this enforcement might be good if children could individually choose what they want to do . It is well -known that these days people , especially students , do not have enough time for extra activities . School work consumes almost every minute of their lives , which should concern the government . PE is one of the most unlikable subjects among teens ; they experience trauma from bullying , some are forced to do activities above their abilities , and the key thing is - everyone is different , but the system grades them the same . Authorities probably want good by forcing to exercise , however they should focus on minimising study hours or how to adjust them for everyone . On the other hand , those 3 PEs per week might be the only form of activity they get during the week . Nowadays , we can assume that this is true , yet shaming pupils for that creates a possibility that , in the future , they will develop disgust to any kind of physical movement . That is why , as a society , we should show a more appealing side of sport so that we do not have to force them to participate in those lessons . All in all , this statement has two sides - a good one and a bad one . Ideally , students will be in shape , including those for whom sport at school is the only form of activity . Nevertheless , individuals who are not keen on doing sport might get traumatised and never ' touch ' it again . 
I usually sleep in a quiet room with some light . This light comes from a lamppost near my house . At first it bothered me , but today it does not bother me anymore . To have quality sleep , you need at least 8 hours of sleep . I can sleep this many hours only if my room is dim and silent because I do not like noise . Sometimes the noise of cars and buses passing in the street wakes me up early in the morning . I did not like it , but over time I have got used to it too . 
We live in a world that supposedly revolves around self -care . The widespread tendency these days , though , is a lack of physical work . How often do we run into a person , especially young , who exercises regularly ? Sadly , to majority of adolescents ' minds , there are other , more meaningful priorities in life than health . Quite a thought -provoking solution with a view to terminating this baffling speculation is to make all students and children exercise . Firstly , it is generally held that lacking in physical exercising equals struggling with health . Furthermore , I believe that modern technology is a nail in teenagers ' tombs . The fact that perfectly illustrates it is their frequent preferences of spending their leisure time on Instagram rather than cycling or jogging . Is not that frustrating ? What 's more , from the psychological standpoint , an order of exercising at least 3 times per week can be motivating for youngsters . What I mean is , as soon as they set their aim , they allow themselves to gain self -confidence , which is maintained as utterly useful at their age . Referring to my previous arguments , another convincing fact is that teenagers and students can be sometimes overly careful with their future lives . Keeping in mind that sport facilitates them to maintain a healthy lifestyle , exercising will benefit them well , perhaps in 10 years ' time . On the other hand , however , forcing kids to exercise can cause dreadful anxiety because of the pressure they 'd be put under . Vitally , in my view , a more effective way would include conversations with young people , lessons and articles encouraging them to take up some sport . Taking everything into consideration , I come to the conclusion that awareness about the benefits of exercising should be spread among children and students . This way , it is highly likely that they will naturally decide to become athletic all by themselves . By and large , surely , exercising at least 3 times a week is recommended for them ! 
