I will point out my view regarding the question of whether I prefer working in cubicles or in an office with a more open design . At the beginning , every employee needs to be capable of carrying out his work . Thus , the colleagues must behave appropriately in order to create a conforme atmosphere . If this is the case , I do not see difficulties in offices whose design is more open , but rather advantages . Referring to this , the team spirit of the employees could be strengthened and they could stand by their colleagues to compensate their individual weaknesses . Additionally , the atmosphere would be more communicative and the personnel would feel more convivial . In contrast to this , the circumstances are in cubicles sometimes better because office work matters a bulk of movement and much conversation about various issues . This can be irritating for an outstanding person , who focuses on another task and hardly concentrates . By taking all this into consideration , I safely assume that this question can only be answered individually as it depends on the colleagues you have at work . 
We are living in a society in which the number one cause of death are cardiovascular related diseases , which are in terms mainly influenced by factors like activity and nutrition . This poses , rightfully so , the question of whether the national government should consider a mandatory sports membership in a sports club . Starting of with the legitimacy . Of course , such a policy is considered to be a huge intervention in both parental autonomy and the freedom of the child concerned . However , one can argue that , in health related issues , such interventions can be justified as it is already the case of other health care issues and preemptive medical examinations . Another , often overlooked , challenge is that new policies can result in social injustice and discrimination . Applying this to our case , one notices a need for at least partial public funding of the activities or sports clubs in order to legitimate it . Also a social stigmatisation of the untalented may arise . Looking at efficiency , we have to ask ourselves how well would such a policy induce the desired result without costing too much . Looking at costs might be quite simple if the policy shows any effect , expressed in lowering hospitalization rates at all , the net savings in health insurance costs already finance the regulation . However , one has also pay attention to any bureaucratic challenges entailed by the supervision of such a regulation . Another argument against this case is that most cardiovascular related diseases only arise at a certain age and school children are virtually unaffected . The only thinkable benefit would be the building of healthy habits at a young age and the establishment of a more prominent role of sports in our society in general . As you can see , a similar regulation entails many potential consequences . And one important question remains unanswered , is the intervention in our children 's freedom worth the possibly small benefits ? 
